related_questions.question: Is whole wheat bread healthier?
related_questions.snippet: Bread made from whole grains, including whole wheat and sprouted whole grain, typically offers the most nutrients. Dozens of varieties of bread line store shelves and fill cookbooks, though some are more nutrient-dense than others. Certain types are naturally high in fiber, vitamins, and minerals.
related_questions.title: The 7 Healthiest Types of Bread - Healthline

related_questions.question: What is the difference between brown bread and whole wheat bread?
related_questions.snippet: Difference Between Brown Bread vs Whole Wheat Bread Brown bread doesn't contain bran, endosperm, and germ that whole grain bread does, making it nutritionally inferior in vitamins, protein, fat, and carbohydrate. Whole wheat bread contains more fibre than brown bread made with a high concentration of refined flour.

related_questions.question: Is wholewheat bread the same as wholemeal bread?
related_questions.snippet: Wholemeal, wholewheat and wholegrain bread are basically different terms for the same thing and all are wholegrain. However, granary bread is slightly different and refers to bread that contains malted wheat flakes that are added to give it a characteristic texture.

buttons.subtitle: Why Is 100 Whole Wheat Bread Healthy
buttons.title: Is whole wheat bread actually healthier? Here's what experts say.
buttons.snippet: Whole wheat bread is made from whole grains as opposed to refined grains — which is what white bread is made from. Whole grains contain nutrients such as fiber, B-vitamins and vitamin A that you won't find in white bread, according to the Mayo Clinic.
snippet_highlighted_words: Whole grains contain nutrients such as fiber, B-vitamins and vitamin A that you won't find in white bread

buttons.subtitle: Wheat Bread Carbs
buttons.title: Whole Wheat Bread Nutrition Facts and Health Benefits - Verywell Fit
buttons.snippet: Whole wheat bread is loaded with complex carbohydrates, which take longer for the body to process and tend to impact blood sugar at a slow, steady pace. An average slice contains anywhere from about 12 to 20 grams of total carbohydrates, a significant amount of which are fiber (3 grams per slice).
